T1  - Monetary policy and labor market frictions: A tax interpretation
AU  - Ravenna, Federico
AU  - Walsh, Carl E.
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 59
IS  - 2
SP  - 180
EP  - 195
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/03/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jmoneco.2012.01.003
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304393212000190
AB  - Replicating the flexible price allocation in models with nominal rigidities and labor market frictions that lead to an inefficient matching of unemployed workers with job vacancies, even if feasible, is generally not desirable. We characterize the tax instruments that implement the first best allocation and examine the trade-offs faced by monetary policy if these tax instruments are unavailable. Our tax interpretation helps explain why the welfare cost of inefficient labor market search can be large while the incentive to deviate from price stability is small. Gains from deviating from price stability are larger in economies with more volatile labor flows.
